abstract: ST. LOUIS, Aug. 26 (AP)--Cesar Cedeno's fifth career grand slam highlighted a six-run uprising in the fifth inning tonight, powering the Houston Astros to a 7-2 triumph over the St. Louis Cardinals.

abstract: Prosperity and the Mets continued to be strangers yesterday. Two home runs by Claudell Washington, a pinch homer by Jose Moreno and four innings of one-hit relief pitching by Neil Allen all went for naught as New York was defeated by San Diego, 8-6, in 18 innings.

abstract: LONDON, Aug. 25--Steve Ovett of Britain, the world-record holder, outsprinted Steve Scott of the United States and won the Golden Mile race today at the Crystal Palace.

abstract: EL TORO, Calif., Aug. 23--More and more cities and other public agencies are requiring builders to price some new homes within the means of middle-income families. In many cases, they are also forbidding buyers to make large profits when they eventually sell such homes.
headline_main: Cities Seek to Get Homes Priced for Middle Class; 'The Next Social Battlefield' Action in Congress on Rentals Dispute Over Who Should Act Cautious Acceptance by Builders

abstract: CLEVELAND--There are three kinds of business situations, in the opinion of John G. Breen. "There are growth situations, maintenance, and turnaround. And when you're in a turnaround situation you've got to move."

abstract: The New York Mets ended their seven-game losing streak yesterday when they defeated the San Francisco Giants, 5-1. But they continued their soap-opera streak of injuries when Craig Swan left after two innings with soreness in the same right shoulder that had cost him a month of pitching this summer.
headline_main: Mets End Skid, but Sore Shoulder Idles Swan Again; Torre 'Very Disturbed' Falcone Settles Down Mets End Skid at 7, But Lose Swan Again Astros 12, Pirates 5 Mets Box Score

abstract: Senator Harrison A. Williams Jr. of New Jersey met last summer with an undercover agent for the Federal Bureau of Investigation posing as an Arab sheik who was willing to bribe American public officials for political favors, the Senator's attorney confirmed yesterday.
